<p><strong>Approaching an event (Networking Events, Dates, Meeting New People etc.)</strong></p>

<ul>
  <li>Get Pre event practice and momentum by talking to Baristas, Co-workers etc. for 1-3 minutes.
    <ul>
      <li>Wrong question â€œHow do I start a conversation with [Specific Magic Snowflake Person]?â€</li>
      <li>Right question: â€œHow many people have you ALREADY started conversations with today?
        <ul>
          <li>With each small conversation you start, youâ€™re actually doing two things at once:
            <ul>
              <li>Youâ€™re building the skill of starting conversations. Skills are something that you can improve over time, and they become a core part of who you are and how you see the world.</li>
              <li>Newtonâ€™s first law: An object in motion stays in motion. Youâ€™re building momentum so that you can start more conversations throughout your day. Itâ€™s a virtuous cycle.</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Play the host</strong> Approach and Be approachable. Exude calm and sense of security, that is â€œI do not care  about what other people think.â€ Be at home, instead of being like an intruder. Â  Moving comfortably and gracefully. Spreading out your body to full comfort. Taking up a lot of space with your body. Sit where you will be noticed. Move with courage and confidence.Â  Keep your body language open, tall, and engaging. Lean back, relax, smile, people watch, and make eye contact.Â You, nicely dressed, peppy, walk with charisma into the room, and act like you own the damn place.Â  Imagine yourself as the man, and everybody else like an inanimate object.Â  Feel as if youâ€™ve built the building, like youâ€™ve invited everyone to the party, like the people are yours to own.Â  This may turn some folks off, but you donâ€™t care about those.Â   Walk in with a smile.Â Remember, other people are shy and anxious as well!Â Â Â  Introduce yourself.Â </p>
  </li>
  <li><strong>Assume Everyone is Your Friend And Youâ€™re likeable</strong> When I go into the room, I act like everyone is already my friend. I will talk with them about what I talk to friends about, once we have a bit of rapport, Iâ€™ll tease them a bit, like I would a friend. Even if they are cold to me upfront, I donâ€™t let that change how I act towards them. Eventually, most people eventually warm up, because itâ€™s exhausting trying to be mean to someone whoâ€™s treating you like their friend.</li>
