<p><strong>Have a good elevator pitch but throww it out along with other social scripts (How are you?) for a memorable conversation</strong> - who you are and what you bring to the tableÂ  tell your story well and concisely. You want to give the other person a good idea of your skills, qualifications, and where youâ€™re looking to go in your career. How do some people seem to wind up with advocates everywhere? They create a little mental model of themselves that makes it easy for everybody they meet.Everybody has a â€œprojectionâ€ - a small representation - of each person they know living in their heads. You know that friend whoâ€™s â€œthe badass interface designer who is looking to get into machine learning and consults?â€ She has an amazing projection and makes it easy for opportunities to find her.. In order to maximize the effectiveness of your projections, figure out which things you want to be associated with in peopleâ€™s heads and be excited about them. Nothing is more memorable than distinct excitement. Similarly, try to figure out the things that drive the whomever youâ€™re talking to and incorporate them into your mental representation of that person. The best way to encourage people to keep you in mind is to keep them in mind. (NOTE: Many people take this to the extreme and straight up ask the question: â€œhow can I help?â€ This is exactly the sentiment you should have, but it makes your counterpart feel like you werenâ€™t actually listening How do you build a strong projection? A strong story. Stories stick in peopleâ€™s heads better than anything else. Make sure you have a good one. All you need is a short narrative with at least one compelling character (you), a captivating theme, and some kind of narrative arc. Think about your life as a series of towns connected by a road, where the towns are the relevant parts of your background connected by your theme. Frankly, most people wonâ€™t remember the towns at all. Theyâ€™ll just viscerally remember wheth