<p><strong>How to have a memorable conversation?</strong>
Â </p>

<blockquote>
  <p>Smalltalk a request to engage only in this non-verbal connection for a fleeting moment.Â You donâ€™t need to be â€œgoodâ€ at it. It really doesnâ€™t matter what you say. Say anything and the ball keeps rolling for a few moments longer. You can find compassion towards the person who initiates it instead of contempt: They are actually asking to warm by your fire for a little bit. They are not testing/dueling you.</p>
</blockquote>

<blockquote>
  <p>Smalltalk is improv. Itâ€™s yesâ€¦ and. You take turns with the hot potato. You take your turn and then pass it. Itâ€™s creating a story. Take whatever what was passed to you, add something quirky and then pass it back. Itâ€™s fun to add something off the wall, a bit ridiculous. Doing this takes courage. You WILL make mistakes. At times, you may cringe at yourself. Putting yourself out there, taking small risks is the spice of life. When you fail, embrace it and move on. Donâ€™t look back. If you smile and keep a bright attitude, then that becomes infectious. If showing up is 90%, then the right attitude is showing up. The quickest way to screw this up is to be toxic.</p>
</blockquote>

<p><strong>Keep a positive attitude (donâ€™t forget the smile) even when youâ€™re feeling attacked.</strong> If you canâ€™t bear it, then keep a number of exit strategies in your bag of tricks and pull one of them. You have to get going. Someone is expecting you. You need to take a call, etc. If you choose to stay, then you have to stay deft and keep the air light. Donâ€™t let someone pin you down into a corner where you have to defend yourself. Continue keeping things light and a bit ridiculous and the air will change. You might even gain some respect.</p>

<p>Sometimes small talk is good. E.g. elevator Pitches for networking events, or where the engagement is formal. Break small talk only when you want to.</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>My first chance to put this new strategy into practice came with a woman I met at a party a few weeks later. She laughed when I explained my theory on big talk versus small talk and agreed to be the guinea pig. She was moving away the next week, so we both knew weâ€™d have only this one date, but we pledged to do all we could to avoid small talk. That night, we talked big and we talked deep. I learned about her brotherâ€™s drug problem, about the ex she had left years before and about the feelings she still had for him. But we also joked about things both silly and shallow, managing to convince strangers that we had met in a fairground bumper-car accident, and recoiling in mock fright from a meal that was still wiggling on our plates. We laughed and we cried, and we learned nothing that would go on a rÃ©sumÃ©. Later, we kissed.</p>
</blockquote>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Anchor on something common, reveal about you, encourage with a question</strong>. Start anywhere. All starting points are equally valid. (â€˜Nice weather weâ€™re having). Begin with what seems obvious or  your inner Rolodex of topics.   Once it is under way any task seems smaller. Trust your mind.Â  Edit and develop ideas as you speak. What is ordinary to you is often a revelation to others.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <blockquote>
      <p>â€œHow are you?â€ Move the short conversation forward by replyingÂ whyÂ youâ€™re â€œgood.â€ â€œIâ€™m good. I just started a book/podcast/TV show and Iâ€™m really enjoying it. Have you heard of it?â€ Or mention something office-related, where thereâ€™s a shared common experience: â€œIâ€™m good. They restocked the cold brew in the kitchen and itâ€™s so strong. Have you tried it?â€</p>
    </blockquote>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Find a common connection: a hobby or achievement or common friend of your own.</strong>Â </li>
      <li>
        <p>But eliminate the dull droning on about facts and figures â€” whether itâ€™s snowing or raining, how cold it is, what we do for work, how long it takes to get to work, where we went to school â€” all those things that we think we have to talk about with someone new but that tell us little about who the person really is. Replace mindless chatter about commuting times with a conversation about our weightiest beliefs and most potent fears. Questions that reveal who we are and where we want to go</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Unless you really know what youâ€™re doing, you should keep the conversation to safe, professional topics. Ask questions about their work that you genuinely want answered. Ask them about the people they work with. Figure out who you know (that is, professionally) in common. Say things like, â€œI hear that your school has started a new such-and-such program; is that something you were involved in?â€, or â€œSo-and-so from your group joined our faculty recently; nice person, interesting workâ€. If other people, projects, or laboratories come up in the conversation, say whatever positive things you honestly have to say about them â€“ avoid criticism and negativity.</p>
      </li>
      <li><strong>Something common can be  memory you experienced together.</strong>Â Memories create an instant connection. When you see someone you know, instead of just saying, â€œHey, how are you doing?â€ (which is pretty much what every single person will say to them), start with a memory.  For example, â€œHey, remember that time when we all went out in Hollywood and ended up singing â€˜Hey Judeâ€™ at that dueling piano bar?Â  That was so fun!â€ I can almost guarantee youâ€™ll get a better reaction.Â   The story of how you met can be particularly powerful and connecting, because it is, essentially, your origin story. And itâ€™s always a happy memory. â€œEverything was pure then, nothing hurt yet,â€ Highlighting great memories or successes that you had together in the past helps you reconnect.</li>
      <li><strong>Reveal yourself. This can include stories about your â€œfirsts.â€</strong> If you arenâ€™t used to telling each other stories, itâ€™s useful to have a few topics ready. Your first anythingâ€”date, kiss, dance, car, child, house, is a great place to start.  Tell stories of the past, present and future. Narrating recent events that have happened to you, or telling a story about a challenge you are facing, helps illuminate what matters to you. Weaving a story of a future event as youâ€™d like it to happenâ€”a vacation, a childâ€™s wedding, the dance at your 60th anniversary partyâ€”can help you visualize what you want for your relationship</li>
      <li><strong>At the end of each topic or blurb, throw out a conversational spark.</strong> The purpose of the conversational spark is toâ€¦you guessed it, spark a further conversation.
        <ul>
          <li>Â â€œâ€¦what do you guys think? Would you rather A or B?â€Â â€œâ€¦If you got paid $1,000 would you do XYZ?â€</li>
          <li>Â Â â€œâ€¦ I canâ€™t believe they did that, what would you guys do in that situation?â€</li>
          <li>Â You could just go in with the â€œWould you ratherâ€¦?â€ game. Use with caution.Â 
            <ul>
              <li>Â Would you rather : Have a good holiday which you remember, or a great holiday which you forgetâ€¨?</li>
              <li>Â Artist or Happyâ€¨</li>
