  <li>
    <p><strong>Ask questions.</strong> Weâ€™re all ultimately pretty narcissistic at heart.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Food</strong>.â€¨ Youâ€™ll rarely find someone who canâ€™t spout a Shakespearean-esque monologue about their favorite meals. 
      * â€œIâ€™m so hungry Greg. If I was being executed tonight, my last meal would be a full rack of BBQ ribs and a bucket of onion rings. What would you have?â€
      * â€œSusan, I had the most fantabulous gelato the other day. Guava strawberry with a wafer on top. You lean more towards ice cream or yogurt?â€ 
      * Note: I purposefully exaggerated the sensibilities of Susan and Greg. This isnâ€™t indicative of how I think men vs women operate in the world. Theyâ€™re just familiar archetypes I think many have experience with before.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Discuss things you care about</strong> Topics relating to your professional field, for example, an article you saw or book you read, is a great place to start.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Something weird or interesting happen to you recently.</strong>Â WorkshopÂ (in your mind, at least) that story ahead of time to unveil at your next office outing.</p>
  </li>
  <li><strong>Open ended questions</strong>
    <ul>
      <li>One of the common questions I find myself asking a woman on a first date is where she has traveled. The response can quickly become a list of places, and once again weâ€™re in rÃ©sumÃ© territory. So instead Iâ€™d ask, â€œWhat place most inspired you and why?â€</li>
      <li>Rather than ask about her job, I would ask, â€œWhat work are you passionate about?â€</li>
      <li>I wouldnâ€™t ask about her longest relationship, as if length equals depth. Instead, Iâ€™d ask, â€œWhatâ€™s the most in love youâ€™ve ever felt?â€</li>
      <li>Aim for questions that invite people to tell stories, rather than give bland, one-word answers.</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

