<p>Mirrored example:
James: Itâ€™s a beautiful day!
John: Yes, it is a beautiful day!</p>

<p>See? By mirroring Jamesâ€™s opinion and language, John has followed the social norm, but heâ€™s also paralyzed the discussion and missed a moment of fun. Instead, John needs to practice the art of disruption and move the dialogue forward:</p>

<p>Non-mirrored example:
James: Itâ€™s a beautiful day!
John: They say that the weather was just like this when the Japanese bombed Pearl Harbor. If that actually happened.</p>

<p>Leapfrog over the expected response
An even better way to break the boring-conversation mirror is to skip over the expected response, and go somewhere next-level:</p>

<p>Instead of :
Ron: How was your flight?
Carlos: My flight was good!</p>

<p>Beverly: Itâ€™s hot today.
