<p><strong>Situation: How to shake hands?</strong></p>

<p>Someone else said something to the effect of â€œTurn your hand over so your palm is facing down. That shows dominance.â€ Okay sure, but do you always want to show dominance? Is it ALL ALPHA ALL THE TIME with you? If so, you might be a jerk.
You should be able to divide the people with whom you shake hands into three rough categories:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Shy people should be offered the hand palm-up. Youâ€™re showing them that youâ€™re not threatening, and you arenâ€™t going to impose your ego on them the whole time youâ€™re together. Thereâ€™s no squeeze hereâ€“ Just a gentle cup, like youâ€™re holding a palmful of water. Youâ€™re also extending your arm far away from your body, somewhat unbalancing yourself for their sakeâ€“ If this was judo, you would be pretty much opening yourself up for a big throw. Youâ€™re saying, â€œHere, let me leave my comfort zone so you donâ€™t have to.â€ I have a friend who brings dates to group events alot. His dates donâ€™t know anyone else there, so theyâ€™re almost always uncomfortable and shy. This is how I shake their hands.</li>
  <li>Moderate people should be given what I call the car key maneuver. You start with a slight palm-up tilt and turn to a vertical-to-slight palm down tilt. Youâ€™re pretty much just meeting them in the middle here. Most handshakes fall into this category. Donâ€™t overthink it.</li>
  <li>Truly aggressive, arm-wrenching, hand-crushing people should be dealt with in one of two ways:
    <ul>
      <li>Show that brute that you arenâ€™t to be bullied! As you clasp the hand, focus on reaching your fingers as deeply toward the wrist as you firmly hook the thumb with yours. This prevents your fingers from getting crushed. Keep your elbow close to your body to maintain strength and force him to step in. You ready? Cause itâ€™s GO TIME! Twist his wrist until your palm is FLAT or his wrist pops off, pull your arm in closer to your body so he loses his balance, and STARE HIM STRAIGHT IN THE EYES UNTIL HE LOOKS AWAY! He will respect you more if you literally judo throw him.</li>
      <li>Avoid the alpha-dog contest altogether and go for a fist bump. The greatest general is the one who never engages in open combat.</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<hr />

<p><strong>Good practice: Care about names. Situation: I donâ€™t remember/know their name but itâ€™s too late to ask</strong></p>

<ul>
  <li>People will connect with you much better if you show that theyâ€™re important to you. One of the best ways to do this is to remember their names. How?
    <ul>
      <li>Repeat someoneâ€™s name right after they introduce themselves to me.</li>
      <li>Think of a celebrity that has the same name so that it helps my memory by association.</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>But You donâ€™t care about someoneâ€™s name, you care about how the interaction goes and how they make you feel.
    <ul>
      <li>Iâ€™ve had so many sales people trying to build comfort with me by mentioning my name every 10 seconds after I introduced myself it actually becomes unpleasant, I know where this is going. A close friend would not say my name 10 times per minute.</li>
      <li>What I do instead if I really see I actually click with a person and realize I totally forgot their name, I just ask them to say my name again.</li>
      <li>â€œDo you remember my name? You will notice that 3/4 times they would have also forgotten and then you just polarize and laugh, â€œHaha Itâ€™s fine I also forgot, letâ€™s introduce ourselves againâ€. It takes the pressure of your shoulders and makes you more relaxed. If they actually remember, just say â€I totally forgot your name, I didnâ€™t think we would be talking such interesting things, what was it again?â€ while smiling</li>
      <li>Introduce them to someone else. Call over your friend Steve, turn back to the person you were speaking to and say, â€œThis is my friend Steve.â€ Pause. The other person will reveal his/her name to Steve and you will hear it. If you donâ€™t have a friend named Steve, a friend with another name can also work. In a pinch, you can use a waitress with a nametag.</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

